{"cursor":"9958","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox scientist |image = Steven_H_Strogatz.jpg  |image_size = 150px | |name =\nSteven H. Strogatz |caption = |birth_date = |birth_place = |death_date =\n|death_place = |residence = |citizenship = |nationality =American |ethnicity =\n|field = Applied mathematics Complex systems |work_institutions = Cornell\nUniversity |alma_mater = Princeton University Cambridge University Harvard University |doctoral_advisor = |doctoral_students = |known_for =\nDynamical systems theory Network theory |author_abbrev_bot =\n|author_abbrev_zoo = |influences = |influenced = |prizes = |religion =\n|footnotes = }}\n\n'Steven Henry Strogatz' (born August 13, 1959, Torrington, Connecticut) is an\nAmerican mathematician and the Jacob Gould Schurman Professor of Applied\nMathematics at Cornell University. http://www.stevenstrogatz.com/ Strogatz\npersonal web\npage https://www.mae.cornell.edu/people/profile.cfm?netid=shs7\nStrogatz at Cornell He is known for his contributions to the study of\nsynchronization in dynamical systems, and for his work in a variety of areas of\napplied mathematics, including mathematical biology and complex network theory.\n\nIn particular, his 1998 Nature paper with Duncan Watts, entitled \"Collective\ndynamics of small-world networks\", is widely regarded as a seminal\ncontribution to the interdisciplinary field of complex networks, whose\napplications reach from graph theory and statistical physics to sociology,\nbusiness, epidemiology, and neuroscience. As one measure of its importance, it\nwas the most highly cited article about networks between 1998 and 2008, and the\nsixth most highly cited paper in all of physics. [http://sciencewatch.com/inter/aut/2008/08-\ndec/08decWattsET/ ScienceWatch December 2008]\n\nStrogatz's writing includes the 1994 textbook Nonlinear Dynamics and Chaos,\nthree popular books, and frequent newspaper articles. His book, published in\n2009, The Calculus of Friendship, was called \"a genuine\ntearjerker\" [http://www.bookslut.com/nonfiction/2009_09_015101.php Bookslut\nbook review for The Calculus of Friendship] and \"part biography, part\nautobiography and part off-the-beaten-path guide to calculus\". [http://www.americanscientist.org/bookshelf/pub/a-growing-\naffinity American Scientist book review for The Calculus of Friendship]\nHis trade book Sync was chosen as a Best Book of 2003 by Discover Magazine. [http://discovermagazine.com/2003/dec/reviews-best-of-\n2003/article_view?b_start:int=1 Discover's Best Books 2003] Strogatz also\nfilmed a series of lectures on chaos theory for the Teaching Company, released\nin 2008, [http://www.news.cornell.edu/stories/Nov08/strogatzChaos.lg.html\nCornell University Press Release] and, in late January 2010, Strogatz\nbegan writing a weekly column on mathematics in [[The New York Times]]. [http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/01/31/from-fish-to-\ninfinity First New York Times Math Column] These columns, along with many\nothers penned by Strogatz, now appear in a book The Joy of X released in October\n2012. [http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/05/09/the-hilbert-hotel/\nFinal New York Times Math Column] The New York Times columns have been\ndescribed as \"must reads for entrepreneurs and executives who grasp that\nmathematics is now the [[lingua franca]] of serious business analysis.\" [http://blogs.hbr.org/schrage/2010/04/sorry-paul-too-bad-\ntom.html Harvard Business Review blog by Michael Schrage]\n","linknr":272,"url":"Steven_H._Strogatz","recorded":1371235483,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Steven_Strogatz&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Steven_Strogatz&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Steven_Strogatz","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.g